body:
This code doesn't lead to a complaint, but it should, because `this.` is missing at `foo`:

```
class Xyz {
  private int foo = 1;
  int bar() {
    return test(() -> foo); // error is here, must be "this.foo"
  }
  int test(Function<Integer, Integer> fun) {
    return fun.apply(1);
  }
}
```

This code must lead to a complaint:

```
class Foo {
  private String test = "";
  void bar(String test) { // error is here
    System.out.println("Hello: " + test);
  } 
}
```

Because the name `test` hides the name of the existing attribute `this.test`.
